data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction block can be replaced:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — simple lambda with conditionals
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` machinery is no longer needed (or accepted).

---

### 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified and nested paths changed

Two related changes:

- **Duplicate property names across complex types** (e.g., `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to disambiguate. This generates a column-rename migration.
- **Nested complex types** now use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin column names explicitly so no migration renames occur:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // ... other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            // Pin to the OLD name if you don't want a rename migration
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on the interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL safe for logging). Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** method signatures on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.

---

**Summary:** The expression tree rewrite is the biggest win — it eliminates ~15 lines of reflection-heavy code. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes. After making these changes, generate a new EF migration to verify no unexpected column renames sneak in from the complex-type naming changes.
